fields.description:
Currently, Bamboo is hardcoded to schedule branch expiry at 3am daily.
{code:borderStyle=solid|title=BranchExpiryScheduler.java}
 trigger = TriggerUtils.makeDailyTrigger(BRANCH_EXPIRY_TRIGGER, 3, 0);
{code}

In some cases, this might not be ideal as Bamboo is shut down during off office hours on costing reasons (EC2 hosting example).

Since builds expiry schedule is configurable, it would be a good idea to have branch expiry run together with build expiry.

h3. Solution
Bamboo 5.15 introduces system property that allows to configure branch expiry trigger time:
{code:java}
    /**
     * Configure at what time should branch expiry run. Value should represent a valid time and is parsed using {@link java.time.format.DateTimeFormatter#ISO_LOCAL_TIME}
     * <p>Usage: <pre>-Dbamboo.branch.expiry.schedule="04:56"</pre>
     */
    public static final SystemProperty BRANCH_EXPIRY_SCHEDULED_TIME = new SystemProperty(false,
                                                                                         "bamboo.branch.expiry.schedule");
{code}

I suggest updating an instruction on the following document: [Integrating Bamboo with HipChat|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BAMBOO/Integrating+Bamboo+with+HipChat].

At the *Configure Bamboo plans to send notifications to your HipChat server* section,we have:
{quote}
1 - Specify the  hipchat.api.url system property that is used when Bamboo is starting. The hipchat.api.url value must be set to the URL of the organization's HipChat server.
{quote}
It does not give good references on how to do that. I suggest changing this line to:
{quote}
1 - Specify the hipchat.api.url system property that is used when Bamboo is starting, by adding *-Dhipchat.api.url=<my_hipchat_api_url>* to your JVM arguments as per [Configuring system properties|https://confluence.atlassian.com/bamboo/configuring-system-properties-289277236.html#Configuringsystemproperties-ConfiguringBamboosystemproperties].
{quote}
or something similar to it

h3. Problem Definition
Bamboo 5.12 introduced new way to store artifacts at Bamboo home folder. It's independent from plan key now. There's no way to access this storage tag during a build outside of the directory provided from querying the REST API: https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BAMBOO/Plan+directory+information+REST+API

h3. Suggested Solution
It should be possible to get storage tag value from build variables, like {{$\{bamboo.plan.storageTag\}}}

h3. Workaround 
The storage tag is static and won't change for a plan. While far from ideal, if you know this value you can create it as a plan variable manually for use within your build.

The following SQL will show you your plan to storage tag mappings:
{code:sql}
SELECT FULL_KEY,STORAGE_TAG FROM BUILD where build_type in ('CHAIN','CHAIN_BRANCH');
{code}

Currently https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BAMBOO/Dedicating+an+agent only states that the agent can only build dedicated plans and non dedicated plans will not be able to utilize the agent. 

However, as pointed out by one of our engineer in the comment section, this exclusivity is mutual to the plan as well. The plan can only be build on agents that is dedicated to it. This is not explained clearly in the documentation:

{quote}
There is also a reciprocal dedication from the entity the agent is dedicated to, in that the entity will not schedule on non-dedicated agents once it has a dedicated agent.
{quote}

This creates logspam in Bitbucket Server like:
{noformat}
2016-05-17 02:27:41,159 ERROR [http-nio-9080-exec-23] *1NH661Ox147x7246108x5 172.30.210.156,172.24.12.146 "POST /rest/build-status/latest/commits/4edfe23ac8b9869a2999809637ba42fba39d6bea HTTP/1.0" c.a.s.i.build.dao.AoBuildStatusDao Multiple build statuses for commitId "4edfe23ac8b9869a2999809637ba42fba39d6bea" and key "JFS-TJSWBP": BuildStatus{name=Jira Software - Software - Bundled Plugins, state=FAILED, url=https://server-gdn-bamboo.internal.atlassian.com/browse/JFS-TJSWBP, added=2016-05-17 02:27:41.02}, BuildStatus{name=Jira Software - Software - Bundled Plugins, state=FAILED, url=https://server-gdn-bamboo.internal.atlassian.com/browse/JFS-TJSWBP-82, added=2016-05-17 02:27:41.024}
{noformat}

h3. Summary
If a build plan is triggered by a JIRA version release, the build trigger fails and the build plan will be broken in Bamboo and will display a blank page when accessed.

h3. Environment
Bamboo Cloud

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a JIRA project with a linked Bamboo project and build plan
# Configure the Bamboo plan to use a repository being synched with JIRA DVCS
# Create a version in JIRA and create an issue that is included in that version
# Add commits in the VCS repository tagged with the issue key of the issue created in the previous step
# Verify that the commits are now associated with the issue via DVCS. Transition the issue to done.
# Release the version and elect to run a new build of the linked Bamboo build plan

h3. Expected Results
Bamboo triggers the build plan on release of the version.

h3. Actual Results
The call to Bamboo to trigger the build plan fails and the following error appears in the JIRA UI.

!jira_releaseTrigger_error.png|thumbnail! 

The REST call to Bamboo results in the following stack trace in the Bamboo application log.

